%I A397828 #13 Jul 16 2026 16:47:09
%S A397828 1,3,4,6,6,12,8,12,12,6,12,12,14,24,12,24,18,12,20,6,8,12,24,12,30,42,
%T A397828 36,24,30,12,32,48,12,18,24,12,38,60,28,12,42,24,44,12,12,24,48,24,56,
%U A397828 30,36,42,54,36,12,24,20,30,60,12,62,96,24,96,42,12,68,18,24,24,72,12,74
%N A397828 Reduced Dedekind psi function: a(p1^e1*...*pN^eN) = lcm((p1+1)*p1^(e1-1), ..., (pN+1)*pN^(eN-1)).
%C A397828 This is the Dedekind psi analog of the reduced totient function A011773: the same lcm-over-coprime-parts rule, with the Euler totient A000010 replaced by the Dedekind psi function A001615.
%C A397828 A composite number k is a Lucas-Carmichael number (A006972) if and only if a(k) divides k+1, in analogy with the fact that a composite number k is a Carmichael number (A002997) if and only if A011773(k) divides k-1.
%H A397828 Daniel Okwor, <a href="/A397828/b397828.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%F A397828 a(p^e) = (p+1)*p^(e-1) = A001615(p^e) for prime powers p^e.
%F A397828 a(n) = lcm{a(p^e)} over the prime power factors p^e of n.
%e A397828 n = 10 = 2*5: a(10) = lcm((2+1)*2^0, (5+1)*5^0) = lcm(3,6) = 6, whereas A001615(10) = 18.
%o A397828 (PARI) a(n) = my(f=factor(n)); lcm(vector(#f~, i, (f[i,1]+1)*f[i,1]^(f[i,2]-1)));
%o A397828 (Python) from sympy import factorint; from math import lcm; a=lambda n: 1 if n==1 else lcm(*[(p+1)*p**(e-1) for p,e in factorint(n).items()])
%Y A397828 Cf. A001615, A011773, A000010, A002322, A006972, A002997.
%K A397828 nonn,easy,new
%O A397828 1,2
%A A397828 _Daniel Okwor_ and _Eric Chen_, Jul 11 2026
